index 0000000..9b4443b
--- /dev/null
+++ b/SOLUTION.md
@@ -0,0 +1,20 @@
+# Solution
+
+Two bugs in `lrucache/cache.py`, both in the LRU recency bookkeeping:
+
+1. **`get()` didn't refresh recency.** Per the docstring, both `get` and `put`
+   count as "use", but `get` only read `self._data[key]` without calling
+   `move_to_end`. This made recently-read entries look least-recently-used,
+   so `test_get_refreshes_recency` failed: reading `"a"` didn't protect it
+   from eviction. Fixed by calling `self._data.move_to_end(key)` before
+   returning the value (after the TTL check, since expired entries are
+   removed rather than promoted).
+
+2. **`put()` evicted on update of an existing key.** The capacity check
+   `len(self._data) >= self.capacity` didn't distinguish "inserting a new
+   key at full capacity" from "overwriting a key that's already present".
+   Since `OrderedDict` doesn't grow when you reassign an existing key,
+   overwriting at full capacity would still trigger an eviction of the
+   least-recently-used entry, incorrectly discarding an unrelated key
+   (`test_updating_existing_key_does_not_evict_others`). Fixed by only
+   evicting when `key not in self._data and len(self._data) >= self.capacity`.
